ont-size:12pt">Union’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eport, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Maintaining World Class Schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, passed unanimously by its 2013 Annual Conference</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> confirmed that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerns about the academisation of the education system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do not neglect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">profound changes taking place in the education system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mean </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">polices in the future based simply on attempts to re-impose arrangements that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">existed in the past </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unlikely to be credible or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficiently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reflective of pertaining circumstanc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the negative aspects of the academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and free schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they are currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> constituted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> invites reflection on the basis upon which any alternative programme might best be established. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In its submission to the independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pearso</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n/RSA Academies Commission, the NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identified ten tests that it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> any future strategy must fulfil in order to address the individual and collective needs, interests and aspirations of pupils, parents, the school workforce and local communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These tests are:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i) Equality of opportunity – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform programmes must seek to promote the development of an education system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> equality of opportunity in terms of admissions, provision and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">educational outcomes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ii) Democratic accountability – R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eform of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> education system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> must be consistent with democratic values and must ensure that all publicly funded institutions are democratically accountable to the communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they serve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iii) Value for money/transparency – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform strategies must seek to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">secure effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> transparency in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relation to the way in which financial resources are allocated across the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and should ensure that all spending commitments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evaluated robustly and objectively against clear economic efficiency and value for money c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">riteria.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iv) Raises standards – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eforms of the school system must be designed to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all pupils are able to access high quality, engaging and relevant leaning opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that secure the highest possible levels of pupil progress and achievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">v) Union recognition – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Approaches to reform must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure that workforce unions a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re properly represented to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the perspectives of teachers, school leaders and other members of the wider school workforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taken into effective account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in strategic planning and decision-making processes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">condition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s are created that support and promote </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">high quality teaching and learning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vi) National </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pay and conditions of service –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform programmes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the operation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nationa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l pay and conditions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> frameworks that ensure that all pupils, regardless of the school they attend, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receive their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">common </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entitlement to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highly skilled, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">motivated and well trained teacher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">terms and conditions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that enable them to work effectively to rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se standards.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vii) Viability – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Approaches to reform must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ensure that all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools and other relevant settings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are viable and sustainable financially and are not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funded on the basis of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sectional or individual short term interests.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">viii) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upportive and co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llaborative approach to community education – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform programmes must secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the adoption and enhancement of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collaborati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve approaches within and between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">institutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, noting, however, that collaboration does not preclude parents from exercising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their legiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rights to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">informed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">choices about the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools or other relevant settings their children might attend.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ix) Rooted within the community – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any reform of the education system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must ensure that schools are rooted within, not set apart from,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and represent the best of the values and aspirations of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">x) Evidence based – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Approaches to reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> must be based on a genuine, considered use of evidence of educational practice, building on consultation betwe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en all stakeholders, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncluding workforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unions.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is evident that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and free schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fail to reflect these critical features of an effective and equitable state education system. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In particular, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is concerned by the impact of the lack of transparency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in academies and free schools in relation to key aspects of governance. Specifically, it is increasingly evident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that this lack of transparency raises important concerns about key elements of governan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce in academies and free schools including in relation to the fair and equitable operation of admissions arrangements and the awarding of contracts for goods and services to private providers. Work undertaken by the Union further highlights issues relating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the extent to which academies and free schools impose additional and inappropriate financial expectations and requirements on pupils’ families and the effectiveness of existing systems for monitoring and holding schools to account for such practice. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e NASUWT would welcome the opportunity to discuss these issues in more detail in through the submission of oral evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urges the Commi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ttee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to take account of the tests set out above in its evaluation of the implications of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Coalition Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt policy in relation to academies and free schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and in the development of its recommendations about the future structure and organisation of the education system in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Educational progres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s and achievement in the academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and free school sectors</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT notes the assertion by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Department for Education (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that schools in the academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been more effective than their maintained school counterparts in raising overall levels of achievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Most recently, the DfE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">claimed that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 national</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pupil performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> data indicates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that GCSE results </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> five times more quickly in academies and free schools than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools in the maintained sector.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> interpretation placed on the official data by the DfE can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not be regarded as credible given that its comparison of o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">verall GCSE achievement growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in academies and maintained schools fails to take effective account </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">generally lower </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prior</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pupil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attainment levels in academies. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evaluation of pupil achievement acro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss schools with comparable levels of prior pupil attainment on admission confirms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that progress levels between academies and maintained schools are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">similar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will also note that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">most recent assessment of the academies programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the National Audit Office (NAO) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">confirmed that it is not possible on the basis of the available evidence to conclude, as the DfE has done, that the expansion of the academies sector has resulted in an increase in levels of pupil attainment and progress </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or that, of itself, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has contributed towards a narrowing of achievement gaps.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In respect of free schools, the Committee will be aware of claims by the DfE that inspection outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> confirm that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> free schools are outperforming schools in the ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intained sector.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However, evaluation of the Ofsted outcomes cited by the Coalition Government confirms that not only is the sample size of free school inspections used to justify this assertion too small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to allow for meaningful comparisons between free sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hools and other forms of school but also that fewer maintained schools judged by Ofsted to be high performing have been inspected since September 2012 due to changes in Ofsted’s approac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h to the inspection of schools. As a result, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attempts on this basis to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">draw comparisons between free schools and other types of school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are invalid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT remains clear that evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education systems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in which school reforms have reflected the Coalition Government’s academies and free schools model ind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">icates t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat in the longer term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approach to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">restructuring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the state education system is likely to place standards and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> narrow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> educational inequalities at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sweden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, where free schools were first introduced, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it has become increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ingly evident they have served to undermine standards and that individual free schools have only been able to improve their results</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as a result of the selection of pupils with ‘better backgrounds’ than those who attended the institutions the free schools h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ad replaced.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The form of competition used in the Swedish free school model has also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">worked</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to undermine parental confidence in the equity and quality of the education system.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The weight of evidence further confirms that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Charter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> movement in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">United States</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">another significant influence on the Coalition Government’s free schools and academies programme, has failed to raise standards or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in respect of a significant number of Charter Schools,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> address inequalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">given</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relative ineffectiveness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for pupils with relatively low prior attainment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is therefore clear that because the academies and free school programmes of the Coalition Government fail to reflect the principles set out elsewhere in this evidence, the ability of the state education system to raise standards and narrow achie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vement gaps will be compromised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the absence of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a significant reconsideration by the DfE of the basis upon which its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approach to reform of school structures is based.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The process for establishing free schools and academies</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aware of the longstanding concerns of the NASUWT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the lack of transparency and accountability of the processes surrounding academy conversion and the creation of free schools.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite the legal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responsibilities of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">governing bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to take key decisio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns over the governance and organisation of schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, some headteachers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of maintained schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have sought to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">take forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> academy conversion without reference </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to governing bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wider consultation with staff, parents and representatives of the lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cal community</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The decision to become an academy school is a highly significant and irreversible step for any school. It has profound implications for children and young people, governors, parents, the local community and staff.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is a decision requiring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> careful thought and consideration, access to detailed and accurate information about what the change of status will mean in practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over the longer term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a fair and open consultation process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It is therefore entirely unacceptable th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at schools can transition to academy status in breach of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> legal requirements in respect of school governing bodies or the views of wider stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT notes that the Committee has given attention previously to the process of ‘forced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academisation’, in which schools deemed to be underperforming or at risk of failure are required to adopt academy status.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">report of the independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pearson/RSA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies Commission has made clear, this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> form of academisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is fundamentally antithet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ical to the pursuit of quality public education for all. It is anti-democratic, contravenes the wishes of parents and other local stakeholders, may result in adverse consequences for children and young people, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">compromises </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the rights of the wor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">kforce in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undermines public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> confidence in public education.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also important to recognise that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is no requirement on proposers to conduct a public consultation whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they intend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o establish a free school,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highlighting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">democratic deficit in the Coalition Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school reform programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Local communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, local authorities and parents are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disenfranchised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from the free school establishment process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they may have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is subject</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">discretion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">free school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">especially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> important consideration in light of the promotion by the Coalition Government of the use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for free schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of unfit sites and buildings and the limitations placed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the Coalition Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the power of local communities to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such practices through the planning system.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consideration of arrangements for the establishment of free schools also invites reflection on the critical role of state schools in pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">moting social cohesion. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The promotion of social cohesion is at the heart of public service provision. Free schools are not premised on the basis of making a meaningful contribution to the promotion of social cohesion. They are deliberately established to s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tand in isolation from the local authority family of schools. There is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore genuine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> potential for them to lead to parents seeking segregated schools, as has happened </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in other education systems where free school models have become established.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will also be aware that evidence from the NAO’s recent review of the free schools programme calls into serious question the value for money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">secured by public expenditure on free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the extent to which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o play an effective role in meeting primary pupil place needs in areas of severe of high shortage.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Issues relating to the ways in which schools can be supported to sus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tain and enhance their performance and the quality and equity of educational opportunities made available to learners are fundamental to the concerns the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has identified in relation to the Coalition Government’s academies programme. It is particularl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y important to recognise that there has, to date, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">formal, local-level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intermediate tier between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">schools and central Government. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n increasingly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> academised system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> compromise the ability of the education system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the economic, strategic an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d democratic functions that an effective intermediate tier is able to secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, all of which work to ensure that standards are maintained and enhanced and that relevant stakeholders can have access to effective arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which they can engage with the work of local schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">establishment of effective intermediate tiers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is a well-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">established feature of education system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s generally regarded as high-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">performing or rapidly improving. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">No</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> education system regarded as ef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fective by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">OECD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any credible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> international comparative studies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> adopts an approach to local oversight and management of the education system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on a comparable basis to that in place currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for academies and free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will have noted the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intention of the DfE to appoint eight regional school Commissioners with wide ranging powers over the approval of academy applications, the monitoring and oversight of academy pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rformance and the operations of academy sponsors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The DfE proposes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the work of each regional Commissioner w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be overseen by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">board of local headteacher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s elected by other headteachers within their region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This change in policy, while signify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing the Coalition Government’s recognition of the failure of the DfE-led scrutiny and oversight model for academies and free schools, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will serve to compound rather than address the issues that have arisen through the absence of an effective int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ermediate ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Specifically, the proposals represent an additional subversion of local democratic processes and will further disenfranchise local communities in relation to the management and governance of the state funded education system. It is a matter of particu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lar concern that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">headteacher boards will represent the principal accountability line for regional Commissioners, given t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat these headteachers will not, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in turn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accountable to teachers and members of the wider school workforce, parents, pupils or community stakeholders. The risks of profound conflicts of interest between the members of headteacher boards and regional Commissioners in relation to decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that mig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ht impact on the schools of board members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concerning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It should also be noted that that the DfE is clear that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role of the Commissioner should not be regarded as an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attempt to establish an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intermediate tier.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ight of the absence of any public consultation prior to the DfE taking steps to implement its regional Commissioner proposals and their potentially negative implications of the effectiveness and integrity of arrangements for the oversight of academies and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">free schools, the Committee should recommend to the DfE that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appointment of regional Commissioners and boards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> suspended until they have been subject to a meaningful process of public consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The alternatives to sponsored academy status t</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hat might be offered to primary schools</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> perceived as underperforming</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the considerations set out in this eviden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is clear that the use of sponsored academy status to seek to address perceived problems of underperformance in any school, including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> those in the primary sector, is inappropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the context of educational standards, concerns about the efficacy and effectiveness of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Coalition Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt’s academies programme relate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the extent to which it seeks to promote competition rather t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">han collab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oration between schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the role that it envisages that academies and free schools will have in establishing a system constituted on this basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It should be noted in this context that the most recent outcomes of the Organisation for Economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Co-operation and Development’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(OECD) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) study have confirmed that competition between education providers does n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ot, of it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">self, raise standards.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT notes the assertion of the Coalition Government that the development of chains of sponsored academies promotes collaboration between schools within chains. However, evidence indicates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ollaboration within academy chains is highly v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ariable in nature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, tends not to take place beyond chain boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and is not subject to the provisions of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">robust, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transparent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national frameworks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as those evident under the previous Government in relation to, for example, 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4-19 consortia or behaviour and attendance partnerships.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As noted above, the NASUWT recognises that to seek to return to previous models of school governance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and organisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may not be appropriate in an increasingly diverse state education system.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l councils can and should continue to have a vital role in public education, but where relations or structures have broken down, alternatives will be needed that are democratically rooted. Any new strategic solutions must secure democratic engagement and r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epresentation in the provision of public education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In practical terms, this imperative means securing approaches to school oversight, management and governance that reflect the principles set out in this evidence. An important ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emplar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the applicatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n of these principles is the work of the Schools Co-operative Society (SCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to promote the principles and values of public education in a context of increasing diversity of provision. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that, applying the framework of cooperation and the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rinciples of mutualism, it is possible to secure diversity and a progressive educational ethos within schools without risk to the principles and values of public education.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The effectiveness of this approach is demonstrated with reference to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ongoing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work of the SCS in supporting school improvement in a wide range of contexts and circumstances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and represents an important </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alternative approaches to sustaining and enhancing further the quality of educational provision in state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funded schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">15</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> NASUWT (2013). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Maintaining World Class Schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. NA